, and the importance of children, Benjamin Bryce examines the formation of a distinct German-Argentine identity. Through a combination of cultural adaptation and a commitment to Protestant and Catholic religious affiliations, German speakers became stalwart Argentine citizens while maintaining connections to German culture. Even as Argentine nationalism intensified and the state called for a more culturally homogeneous citizenry, the leaders of Buenos Aires's German community advocated for a new, more pluralistic vision of Argentine citizenship by insisting that it was possible both to retain one's ethnic identity and be a good Argentine. Drawing parallels to other immigrant groups while closely analyzing the experiences of Argentines of German heritage, Bryce contributes new perspectives on the history of migration to Latin America-and on the complex interconnections between cultural pluralism and the emergence of national cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCultural pluralismzArgentinazBuenos AiresxHistory. 0aEthnicityzArgentinazBuenos AiresxHistory. 0aGermanszArgentinazBuenos AiresxEthnic identityxHistory. 0aNationalismzArgentinazBuenos AiresxHistory. 4aArgentina. 4aCitizenship. 4aGerman migration. 4aGermany. 4aeducation. 4aethnicity. 4alanguage. 4apluralism. 4areligion. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503604353zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503604353423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503604353.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles